To save text to a local file in a JavaScript web app, you can use the `File` and `Blob` APIs. Here's an example of how you could do this:
```
// Create a new Blob object containing the text data
const blob = new Blob([text], {type: 'text/plain'});

// Create a new File object from the Blob
const file = new File([blob], 'filename.txt', {type: 'text/plain'});

// Save the File to the local file system
file.save();
```
This code creates a new `Blob` object containing the text data, and then creates a new `File` object from the `Blob`. Finally, it saves the `File` to the local file system using the `save()` method.

Note that this code will only work in browsers that support the `File` API, such as Chrome or Firefox. In other browsers, you may need to use a different approach, such as using the `download` attribute on an anchor element to initiate a download of the file.
